name: Andorran Franc
bio: The Andorran franc (ADF) was the currency of Andorra. It circulated along with the Andorran peseta (ADP). It was replaced by the euro in 2002.

name: Andorran Peseta
bio: The Andorran peseta (ADP) was the currency of Andorra. It circulated along with the Andorran franc (ADF). It was replaced by the euro in 2002.

name: Utd. Arab Emir. Dirham
bio: The United Arab Emirates dirham (AED) is the currency of the United Arab Emirates. One dirham is divided into 100 fils. The United Arab Emirates dirham is pegged to the US dollar at the exchange rate of 1 USD = 3.6725 AED.

name: Afghan Afghani
bio: The Afghan afghani (AFN) is the currency of Afghanistan. It is subdivided into 100 puls, with these coins being no longer in circulation. The symbol of the Afghan afghani is ؋.

name: Albanian Lek
bio: The Albanian lek (ALL) is the currency of Albania. It was subdivided into 100 qindarka. Qindarka coins are no longer issued due to inflation. The symbol of the Albanian lek is L.

name: Armenian Dram
bio: The Armenian dram (AMD) is the currency of Armenia and Artsakh. It is subdivided into 100 luma. The symbol of the Armenian dram is ֏. The currency’s name ‘dram’ means ‘money’.

name: NL Antillian Guilder
bio: The Netherlands Antillean Guilder (ANG) is the currency of Curaçao and Sint Maarten. It is also known as the Dutch guilder and is subdivided into 100 cents. The symbol of the Netherlands Antillean guilder is NAƒ.

name: Angolan Kwanza
bio: The Angolan kwanza (AOA) is the currency of Angola. The currency was introduced in 1999. The Angolan kwanza is subdivided into 100 centimos. The symbol of the kwanza is Kz. The currency’s name comes from the Kwanza River.

name: Argentine Peso
bio: The Argentine peso (ARS) is the currency of Argentina. The peso symbol is $. The Argentine peso is subdivided into 100 centavos.

name: Austrian Schilling
bio: The Austrian schilling (ATS) was the currency of Austria. It was subdivided into 100 groschen. Its symbol was S or öS. The Austrian schilling was replaced by the euro in 1999.

name: Australian Dollar
bio: The Australian dollar (AUD) is the official currency of Australia and several independent countries and territories in the South Pacific. The Australian dollar is the fifth most traded currency in the world. AUD was established in 1966. It is also called the ‘buck’, ‘dough’ and ‘aussie’.

name: Aruban Florin
bio: The Aruban florin (AWG) is the currency of Aruba. It is subdivided into 100 cents. Its symbol is Afl. The Aruban florin is pegged to the US dollar at the rate of 1 USD = 1.79 AWG.

name: Azerbaijan New Manat
bio: The Azerbaijan manat (AZN) is the currency of Azerbaijan. The currency is subdivided into 100 qəpik. The symbol of the Azerbaijan manat is ₼. There are similarities between the euro and manat banknotes as both were designed by a banknote designer, Robert Kalina.

name: Bosnian Mark
bio: The Bosnia and Herzegovina convertible mark (BAM) is the currency of Bosnia. It is subdivided into 100 fenings. The symbol of the Bosnia and Herzegovina convertible mark is KM. The currency is pegged to the euro at the rate of 1 EUR = 1.95583 BAM.

name: Barbados Dollar
bio: The Barbadian dollar (BBD) is the currency of Barbados. It is subdivided into 100 cents. The symbol of the Barbadian dollar is $ or BBD$.

name: Bangladeshi Taka
bio: The Bangladeshi taka (BDT) is the currency of Bangladesh. It was subdivided into 100 poishas, although these coins are no longer used. The symbol of the Bangladeshi taka is ৳.

name: Belgian Franc
bio: The Belgian franc (BEF) was the currency of Belgium. It was subdivided into 100 centimes. Its symbol was fr. The Belgian franc was replaced by the euro in 2002.

name: Bulgarian Lev
bio: The Bulgarian Lev (BGN) is the currency of Bulgaria. It is subdivided into 100 stotinki. The symbol of the Bulgarian Lev is лв. The currency’s name ‘lev’ derives from the old Bulgarian and means ‘lion’.

name: Bahraini Dinar
bio: The Bahraini dinar (BHD) is the currency of Bahrain. It is subdivided into 1,000 fils. Its symbol is BD. The Bahraini dinar is pegged to the US dollar at the rate of 1 USD = 0.376 BD. As of 2021, it is the second-strongest currency globally, after the Kuwaiti dinar.

name: Burundi Franc
bio: The Burundi franc (BIF) is the currency of Burundi. It is divided into 100 centimes. The symbol used for the Burundi franc is FBu.

name: Bermudian Dollar
bio: The Bermudian dollar (BMD) is the currency of Bermuda. It is subdivided into 100 cents. Its symbol is $ or BD$. The Bermudian dollar is pegged to the US dollar at par.

name: Brunei Dollar
bio: The Brunei dollar (BND) is the currency of Brunei. Its subunit is sen, one-hundredth of the dollar. The currency’s symbol is $ or B$. The Brunei dollar is pegged to the Singapore dollar at par.

name: Bolivian Boliviano
bio: The Bolivian boliviano (BOB) is the official currency of Bolivia. The symbol used for the currency is Bs. The Bolivian boliviano is subdivided in 100 centavos.

name: Brazilian Real
bio: The Brazilian real (BRL) is the official currency of Brazil. It is divided into 100 centavos. The symbol of the Brazilian real is R$.

name: Bahamian Dollar
bio: The Bahamian dollar (BSD) is the currency of The Bahamas. It is subdivided into 100 cents. Its symbol is $ or B$. The Bahamian dollar is pegged to the US dollar at par.

name: Bhutan Ngultrum
bio: The Bhutanese ngultrum (BTN) is the currency of the Kingdom of Bhutan. It is subdivided into 100 chhertums. Its symbol is Nu. The Bhutanese ngultrum is pegged to the Indian rupee at par.

name: Botswana Pula
bio: The Botswana pula (BWP) is the official currency of Botswana. It is subdivided into 100 thebe. The symbol of the Botswana pula is P. As of 2021, the pula is rated as one of the strongest currencies in Africa.

name: Belarusian Ruble
bio: The Belarusian ruble (BYN) is the currency of Belarus. It is subdivided into 100 copecks. The symbol of the Belarusian ruble is Br. In 2016, the old Belarusian ruble (BYR) was replaced by the new Belarusian ruble (BYN).

name: Belize Dollar
bio: The Belize dollar (BZD) is the official currency of Belize. Its symbol is $ or BZ$. The Belize dollar is subdivided into 100 cents. The currency is pegged to the US dollar at the rate of 1 USD = 2 BZD.

name: Canadian Dollar
bio: The Canadian dollar (CAD) is the official currency of Canada. The Canadian dollar was introduced in 1858. CAD is known as a commodity currency. It is the sixth most traded currency in the world.

name: Congolese Franc
bio: The Congolese franc (CDF) is the official currency of the Democratic Republic of Congo. It is subdivided into 100 centimes. The symbol of the Congolese franc is FC.

name: Swiss Franc
bio: The Swiss franc (CHF) is the official currency of Switzerland and Liechtenstein. The Swiss franc was introduced in 1850. CHF is known as a safe-haven currency. The Swiss franc is the seventh most traded currency in the world.

name: Chilean Peso
bio: The Chilean peso (CLP) is the official currency of Chile. It is divided into 100 centavos, but there are no centavo coins in circulation. The symbol of the Chilean peso is $.

name: Chinese Yuan Renminbi
bio: The Chinese yuan renminbi (CNY) is the official currency of the People's Republic of China. The Chinese yuan renminbi was introduced in 1948. CNY is known as one of the world’s reserve currencies and is the eighth most traded currency globally.

name: Colombian Peso
bio: The Colombian peso (COP) is the official currency of Colombia. The COP was introduced in 1837. The symbol of the Colombian peso is $ and COL$.

name: Costa Rican Colon
bio: The Costa Rican colon (CRC) is the currency of Costa Rica. It is subdivided into 100 centimos. The symbol of the Costa Rican colon is ₡. The name of the currency derives from the explorer Christopher Columbus, Cristóbal Colón in Spanish.

name: Cape Verde Escudo
bio: The Cape Verdean escudo (CVE) is the official currency of the Republic of Cape Verde. The $ symbol is typically used to separate decimals, for example, 20$00 indicates 20 escudos. The Cape Verdean escudo is pegged to the euro at the rate of 1 EUR = 110.265 CVE.

name: Cypriot Pound
bio: The Cypriot pound (CYP) was the currency of Cyprus. It was replaced by the euro on 1st January 2008.

name: Czech Koruna
bio: The Czech koruna (CZK) is the currency of the Czech Republic. It is subdivided into 100  haléřů. The symbol of the Czech koruna is Kč. The currency’s name ‘koruna’ means ‘crown’.

name: German Mark
bio: The German mark (DEM) was the currency of Germany. It was subdivided into 100 pfennigs. Its symbol was DM. The German mark was replaced by the euro in 2002.

name: Djibouti Franc
bio: The Djiboutian franc (DJF) is the official currency of Djibouti. It is subdivided into 100 centimes. The symbol used for the Djiboutian franc is Fdj. The currency is pegged to the US dollar at the rate of 1 USD = 177.721 DJF.

name: Danish Krone
bio: The Danish krone (DKK) is the official currency of Denmark, Greenland and the Faroe Islands. The Danish krone is subdivided into 100 øre. The symbol of the krone is kr. The currency is also known as the Danish crown. The krone is currently pegged to the euro.

name: Dominican Peso
bio: The Dominican peso (DOP) is the official currency of the Dominican Republic. The symbol of the Dominican peso is $ and RD$. The peso is subdivided into 100 centavos.

name: Algerian Dinar
bio: The Algerian dinar (DZD) is the official currency of Algeria. It is subdivided into 100 centimes. The symbol for the Algerian dinar is DA.

name: Ecuador Sucre
bio: The Ecuadorian sucre (ECS) was the official currency of Ecuador until 2000. Its symbol was S/. The Ecuadorian sucre was replaced by the US dollar.

name: Estonian Kroon
bio: The Estonian kroon (EEK) was the currency of Estonia. The symbol of the currency was kr. The Estonian kroon was replaced by the euro on 15th January.

name: Egyptian Pound
bio: The Egyptian pound (EGP) is the official currency of Egypt. The symbol of the currency is E£. The Egyptian pound is subdivided into 100 piastres or 1,000 milliemes.

name: Spanish Peseta
bio: The Spanish peseta (ESP) was the currency of Spain. It was subdivided into 100 céntimos. Its symbol was ₧. The Spanish peseta was replaced by the euro in 2002.

name: Ethiopian Birr
bio: The Ethiopian birr (ETB) is the official currency of Ethiopia. It is subdivided into 100 santims. The symbol of the Ethiopian birr is Br. The word ‘birr’ derives from the local language and means ‘silver’.

name: Euro
hypernym: france, spain, portugal, germany, austria, netherlands, luxembourg, belgium, cyprus, estonia, finland, greece, ireland, latvia, lithuania, malta, slovakia, slovenia, italy
bio: The euro (EUR) is the official currency of 19 of the 27 member states of the European Union. As of the first quarter of 2021, the European Union, also known as the eurozone, consists of 27 member countries. The following countries have adopted the euro: Austria, Belgium, Cyprus, Estonia, Finland, France, Germany, Greece, Ireland, Italy, Latvia, Lithuania, Luxembourg, Malta, the Netherlands, Portugal, Slovakia, Slovenia and Spain.

name: Finnish Markka
bio: The Finnish markka (FIM) was the currency of Finland. It was subdivided into 100 pennies. Its symbol was Mk. The Finnish markka was replaced by the euro in 2002.

name: Fiji Dollar
bio: The Fijian dollar (FJD) is the official currency of Fiji. It is subdivided into 100 cents. The symbol of the Fijian dollar is $ or FJ$.

name: Falkland Islands Pound
bio: The Falkland Islands pound (FKP) is the official currency of the Falkland Islands, which are located in the South Atlantic Ocean and belong to the British Overseas Territory. The symbol of the Falkland Islands pound is £ or FK£. The currency is pegged to the British pound at par.

name: French Franc
bio: The French franc (FRF) was the currency of France. It was subdivided into 100 centimes. Its symbol was F or Fr. In the 19th and 20th centuries, the French franc was one of the world’s reserve currencies. The franc was replaced by the euro in 2002.

name: Great British Pound
hypernym: uk, england, scotland, wales, northern ireland, united kingdom, ashley, neil, dave, tim
bio: The pound sterling, or GBP, is the official currency of the United Kingdom. The pound sterling is the oldest currency in continuous use and is the fourth most traded currency in the foreign exchange market, after the US dollar, euro and Japanese yen.

name: Georgian Lari
bio: The Georgian lari (GEL) is the currency of Georgia. It is subdivided into 100 tetri. The symbol of the Georgian lari is ₾.

name: Ghanaian New Cedi
bio: The Ghanaian cedi (GHS) is the official currency of Ghana. It is divided into 100 pesewas. The symbol of the Ghanaian cedi is GH₵.

name: Gibraltar Pound
bio: The Gibraltar pound (GIP) is the currency of Gibraltar. It is subdivided into 100 pennies. Its symbol is £. The Gibraltar pound is pegged to the British pound at par.

name: Gambian Dalasi
bio: The Gambian dalasi (GMD) is the official currency of Gambia. It is subdivided into 100 bututs. The currency’s name comes from the word ‘dala’, a nickname for a 5-French-West-African-franc note.

name: Guinea Franc
bio: The Guinean franc (GNF) is the official currency of Guinea. It is subdivided into 100 centimes but none of them was ever issued.

name: Greek Drachma
bio: The Greek drachma (GRD) was the currency of Greece. It was subdivided into 100 lepta. The symbol of the Greek drachma was ₯. The currency was replaced by the euro on 1st January 2001.

name: Guatemalan Quetzal
bio: The Guatemalan quetzal (GTQ) is the official currency of Guatemala. It is subdivided into 100 centavos. The symbol of the Guatemalan quetzal is Q.

name: Guyanese Dollar
bio: The Guyanese dollar (GYD) is the official currency of Guyana. It is subdivided into 100 cents. The symbol of the Guyanese dollar is $ and G$.

name: Hong Kong Dollar
bio: The Hong Kong dollar (HKD) is the official currency of Hong Kong. The Hong Kong dollar was introduced in 1863. HKD is the ninth most traded currency in the world. It is pegged to the US dollar.

name: Honduran Lempira
bio: The Honduran lempira (HNL) is the official currency of Honduras. It is subdivided into 100 centavos. The symbol of the Honduran lempira is L.

name: Croatian Kuna
bio: The Croatian kuna (HRK) is the official currency of Croatia. It is subdivided into 100 lipa. The symbol of the Croatian kuna is kn.

name: Haitian Gourde
bio: The Haitian gourde (HTG) is the official currency of Haiti. It is subdivided into 100 centimes. The symbol of the Haitian gourde is G.

name: Hungarian Forint
bio: The Hungarian forint (HUF) is the currency of Hungary. It was subdivided into 100 fillér. Coins of the currency’s subunit are no longer in use due to high inflation. The symbol of the Hungarian forint is Ft.

name: Indonesian Rupiah
bio: The Indonesian rupiah (IDR) is the official currency of Indonesia. It is subdivided into 100 sen, although these coins are no longer used due to high inflation. The symbol of the Indonesian rupiah is Rp.

name: Irish Punt
bio: The Irish pound (IEP) was the currency of Ireland. It was subdivided into 100 pennies. Its symbol was £ or IR£. The Irish pound was replaced by the euro in 2002.

name: Israeli New Shekel
bio: The Israeli new shekel (ILS) is the currency of Israel and the Palestinian territories of the West Bank and the Gaza Strip. It is also known as the Israeli shekel and is subdivided into 100 agorot. The symbol of the currency is ₪. The new shekel was introduced in 1986, replacing the old shekel at the rate of 1,000:1.

name: Indian Rupee
bio: The Indian rupee (INR) is the official currency of the Republic of India and is issued by the Reserve Bank of India. The rupee is subdivided into 100 paise. The symbol of the Indian rupee is ₹.

name: Iraqi Dinar
bio: The Iraqi dinar (IQD) is issued by the Central Bank of Iraq. It is subdivided into 1,000 fils. Due to inflation, they are no longer in use. The Iraqi dinar is pegged to the US dollar.

name: Iranian Rial
bio: The Iranian rial (IRR) is the currency of Iran. Its symbol is ﷼. As of 2021, the Iranian rial is the world’s second weakest currency in circulation.

name: Iceland Krona
bio: The Icelandic krona or króna (ISK) is the official currency of Iceland. Its subunit is eyrir, one-hundredth of the krona. The symbol of the Icelandic krona is kr.

name: Italian Lira
bio: The Italian lira (ITL) was the currency of Italy. It was subdivided into 100 centesimi. Its symbol was L. The Italian lira was replaced by the euro in 2002.

name: Jamaican Dollar
bio: The Jamaican dollar (JMD) is the official currency of Jamaica. It is subdivided into 100 cents. The symbol of the Jamaican dollar J$ or JA$.

name: Jordanian Dinar
bio: The Jordanian dinar (JOD) is the official currency of Jordan. The dinar is subdivided into 10 dirhams, 100 qirshes and 1,000 fils. The symbol of the Jordanian dinar is JD. It is pegged to the US dollar at the rate of 1 USD = 0.709 JOD.

name: Japanese Yen
bio: The Japanese yen (JPY) is the official currency of Japan. It is the third most traded currency in the world. The Japanese yen was introduced in 1871. It is also used as the fourth reserve currency, after the United States dollar, euro and British pound in the world.

name: Kenyan Shilling
bio: The Kenyan shilling (KES) is the official currency of Kenya. It is subdivided into 100 cents. The symbol of the Kenyan shilling is KSh

name: Kyrgyzstanian Som
bio: The Kyrgyzstani som (KGS) is the currency of Kyrgyzstan. It is subdivided into 100 tyiyns.

name: Cambodian Riel
bio: The Cambodian riel (KHR) is the official currency of Cambodia. Its subunits are kak, one-tenth of the riel, and sen, one-hundredth of the riel. The symbol of the Cambodian riel is ៛.

name: Comoros Franc
bio: The Comorian franc (KMF) is the official currency of Comoros. It is subdivided into 100 centimes. The symbol of the Comorian franc is CF. The currency is pegged to the euro at the rate of 1 EUR = 491.96775 KMF.

name: North Korean Won
bio: The North Korean won (KPW) is the official currency of North Korea. It is subdivided into 100 chon. The symbol of the currency is ₩. The North Korean won is strictly controlled by the country’s government and can’t be converted into other currencies. Foreign visitors of the country get a special convertible won to use.

name: Korean Won
bio: The South Korean won (KRW) is the official currency of South Korea. It is subdivided into 100 jeon. The symbol of the South Korean won is ₩.

name: Kuwaiti Dinar
bio: The Kuwaiti dinar (KWD) is the official currency of Kuwait. It is subdivided into 1,000 fils. As of 2021, the Kuwaiti dinar is the world’s strongest currency.

name: Cayman Islands Dollar
bio: The Cayman Islands dollar (KYD) is the currency of the Cayman Islands. It is subdivided into 100 cents. Its symbol is $ or CI$. The Cayman Islands dollar is pegged to the US dollar at the rate of 1 KYD = 1.20 USD.

name: Kazakhstan Tenge
bio: The Kazakhstani tenge (KZT) is the currency of Kazakhstan. It is subdivided into 100 tiyn. The symbol of the Kazakhstani tenge is ₸. The currency was adopted in 1993 and replaced the Russian ruble.

name: Lao Kip
bio: The Lao kip (LAK) is the currency of Laos. It is subdivided into 100 att. The symbol of the Lao kip is ₭.

name: Lebanese Pound
bio: The Lebanese pound (LBP) is the official currency of Lebanon. It was subdivided into 100 piasters but they are no longer in use due to high inflation. The currency’s symbol is ل.ل. The Lebanese pound is pegged to the US dollar at the rate of 1 USD = 1,507.5 LBP.

name: Sri Lanka Rupee
bio: The Sri Lankan rupee (LKR) is the currency of Sri Lanka. It is subdivided into 100 cents. The symbol of the Sri Lankan rupee is Rs.

name: Liberian Dollar
bio: The Liberian dollar (LRD) is the official currency of the Republic of Liberia. It is subdivided into 100 cents. The symbol of the currency is L$. The Liberian dollar is used along with the US dollar due to the common history between these two countries.

name: Lesotho Loti
bio: The Lesotho loti (LSL) is the official currency of the Kingdom of Lesotho. It is subdivided into 100 lisente. The Lesotho loti is pegged to the South African rand at par and both currencies are accepted as legal tender in the country.

name: Lithuanian Litas
bio: The Lithuanian litas (LTL) was the currency of Lithuania. The Lithuanian litas was divided into 100 centų. The currency’s symbol was Lt. On 1st January 2015, it was replaced by the euro.

name: Luxembourg Franc
bio: The Luxembourg franc (LUF) was the currency of Luxembourg. It was subdivided into 100 centimes. Its symbol was F. The Luxembourg franc was replaced by the euro in 2002.

name: Latvian Lats
bio: The Latvian lats (LVL) was the currency of Latvia. It was subdivided into 100 santīmi. The symbol of the Latvian lats was Ls. The currency was replaced by the euro in January 2014.

name: Libyan Dinar
bio: The Libyan dinar (LYD) is the official currency of Libya. It is subdivided into 1,000 dirhams. The symbol of the Libyan dinar is LD.

name: Moroccan Dirham
bio: The Moroccan dirham (MAD) is the currency of Morocco. It is issued by the Central Bank of Morocco, the Bank Al-Maghrib. The Moroccan dirham is subdivided into 100 centimes. The symbol of the currency is DH.

name: Moldovan Leu
bio: The Moldovan leu (MDL) is the official currency of Moldova. The leu is subdivided into 100 bani. The symbol of the Moldovan leu is L. The name ‘leu’ derives from Romanian and means ‘lion’.

name: Malagasy Ariary
bio: The Malagasy ariary (MGA) is the official currency of Madagascar. It is subdivided into 5 iraimbilanja. The currency is one of only two circulating currencies, along with Mauritanian ouguiya, globally whose subunit is not based on a power of ten. The symbol of the Malagasy ariary is Ar.

name: Macedonian Denar
bio: The Macedonian denar (MKD) is the official currency of North Macedonia. It is subdivided into 100 denars. The symbol of the Macedonian denar is ден.

name: Myanmar Kyat
bio: The Myanmar kyat (MMK) is the official currency of Myanmar, formerly known as Burma. It is subdivided into 100 pyas. The symbol of the Myanmar kyat is K.

name: Mongolian Tugrik
bio: The Mongolian tugrik or tögrög (MNT) is the official currency of Mongolia. Its symbol is ₮.

name: Macau Pataca
bio: The Macanese pataca (MOP) is the currency of Macau. It is subdivided into 10 ho and 100 sin. The symbol of the Macanese pataca is MOP$.

name: Mauritania Ouguiya
bio: The Mauritanian ouguiya (MRU) is the official currency of Mauritania. It is subdivided into 5 khoums. The currency is one of only two circulating currencies, along with Malagasy ariary, globally whose subunit is not based on a power of ten. The symbol of the Mauritanian ouguiya is UM.

name: Maltese Lira
bio: The Maltese lira (MTL) was the official currency of Malta. The symbol of the currency was Lm and ₤M. The Maltese lira was replaced by the euro in 2007.

name: Mauritius Rupee
bio: The Mauritius rupee (MUR) is the official currency of Mauritius. It is subdivided into 100 cents. The symbol of the Mauritius rupee is Rs.

name: Maldive Rufiyaa
bio: The Maldivian rufiyaa (MVR) is the official currency of the Maldives. It is subdivided into 100 laari. The symbol of the Maldivian rufiyaa is Rf.

name: Malawi Kwacha
bio: The Malawian kwacha (MWK) is the official currency of Malawi. Its subunit is tambala, one-hundredth of the kwacha. The symbol of the Malawian kwacha is K.

name: Mexican Peso
bio: The Mexican peso (MXN) is the official currency of Mexico. It is subdivided into 100 centavos. The currency was initially based on Spain’s official currency, called ‘real’, which was the Spanish dollar. The Mexican peso’s name originated from the silver 8-real coins issued by Spain in Mexico.

name: Malaysian Ringgit
bio: The Malaysian ringgit (MYR), unofficially called the Malaysian dollar, is the official currency of Malaysia. The Malaysian ringgit is divided into 100 sen.

name: Mozambique New Metical
bio: The Mozambican metical (MZN) is the official currency of Mozambique. It is subdivided into 100 centavos. Currencies such as the US dollar, British pound, euro and South African rand are also used in the country.

name: Namibia Dollar
bio: The Namibian dollar (NAD) is the official currency of Namibia. It is subdivided into 100 cents. The symbol of the Namibian dollar is $ or N$. The Namibian dollar is pegged to the South African rand at par, which is also legal tender in the country.

name: Nigerian Naira
bio: The Nigerian naira (NGN) is the official currency of Nigeria. It is subdivided into 100 kobos. The Central Bank of Nigeria is the only bank with the authority to issue the legal currency. The symbol of the Nigerian naira is ₦.

name: Nicaraguan Cordoba Oro
bio: The Nicaraguan cordoba (NIO) is the official currency of Nicaragua. It is subdivided into 100 centavos. The symbol of the Nicaraguan cordoba is C$. The currency has been named after Francisco Hernández de Córdoba, the founder of Nicaragua.

name: Dutch Guilder
bio: The Dutch guilder (NLG) was the currency of the Netherlands. It was subdivided into 100 cents. Its symbol was ƒ. The Dutch guilder was replaced by the euro in 2002.

name: Norwegian Kroner
bio: The Norwegian krone (NOK) is the official currency of Norway. It is subdivided into 100 øre. The symbol of the Norwegian krone is kr. In English, the word ‘krone’ translates to ‘crown’.

name: Nepalese Rupee
bio: The Nepalese rupee (NPR) is the official currency of Nepal. It is subdivided into 100 paisa. The symbol of the Nepalese rupee is रु. The currnecy is pegged to the Indian rupee at the rate of 1 INR = 1.60 NPR.

name: New Zealand Dollar
bio: The New Zealand dollar (NZD) is the official currency of New Zealand and the Cook Islands, Niue, the Ross Dependency, Tokelau, and the Pitcairn Islands. The New Zealand dollar is informally called the ‘kiwi’.

name: Omani Rial
bio: The Omani rial (OMR) is the official currency of Oman. It is subdivided into 1,000 baisa. Its symbol is ر.ع. The Omani rial is pegged to the US dollar at the rate of 1 USD = 0.384497 OMR.

name: Panamanian Balboa
bio: The Panamanian balboa (PAB) is the official currency of Panama. It is subdivided into 100 centésimos and its symbol is B/. The currency has been named after Vasco Núñez de Balboa, a Spanish explorer and conquistador. The Panamanian balboa is pegged to the US dollar at par, which is also used in the country.

name: Peruvian Nuevo Sol
bio: The Peruvian sol (PEN) is the currency of Peru. It is subdivided into 100 céntimos. The symbol of the Peruvian sol is S/.

name: Papua New Guinea Kina
bio: The Papua New Guinean kina (PGK) is the official currency of Papua New Guinea. It is subdivided into 100 toea. The Papua New Guinean kina was issued in 1975 and replaced the Australian dollar. The name ‘kina’ refers to a pearl shell widely used for local trading.

name: Philippine Peso
bio: The Philippine peso (PHP), or ‘piso’ in Filipino, is the official currency of the Philippines. It's subdivided into 100 centavos, or ‘sentimos’ in Filipino. The symbol of the Philippine peso is ₱.

name: Pakistan Rupee
bio: The Pakistani rupee (PKR) is the official currency of Pakistan. It is subdivided into 100 paise. The symbol of the Pakistani rupee is Rs.

name: Polish Zloty
bio: The Polish zloty (PLN) is the currency of Poland. Its subunit is grosz, one-hundredth of the zloty. The symbol of the Polish zloty is zł. The currency’s name ‘zloty’ means ‘golden’.

name: Portuguese Escudo
bio: The Portuguese escudo (PTE) was the currency of Portugal. It was subdivided into 100 centavos. The Portuguese escudo was replaced by the euro in 2002.

name: Paraguay Guarani
bio: The Paraguayan guarani (PYG) is the official currency of Paraguay. It was subdivided into 100 céntimos, but they are no longer in use due to their very low value. The symbol of the Paraguayan guarani is ₲.

name: Qatari Rial
bio: The Qatari riyal (QAR) is the currency of Qatar. It is subdivided into 100 dirhams. Its symbol is ر.ق. The Qatari riyal is pegged to the US dollar at the rate of 1 USD = 3.64 QAR.

name: Romanian New Leu
bio: The Romanian leu (RON) is the currency of Romania. It is subdivided into 100 bani. The symbol of the currency is L. The currency’s name ‘leu’ means ‘lion’.

name: Serbian Dinar
bio: The Serbian dinar (RSD) is the currency used in Serbia. It is subdivided into 100 paras. The symbol of the Serbian dinar is РСД.

name: Russian Rouble
bio: The Russian ruble (RUB) is the official currency of the Russian Federation, as well as South Ossetia, Abkhazia, Donetsk and Luhansk. The ruble is subdivided into 100 kopeks. The symbol of the Russian ruble is ₽.

name: Rwandan Franc
bio: The Rwandan franc (RWF) is the currency of Rwanda. The franc is subdivided into 100 centimes.

name: Saudi Riyal
bio: The Saudi riyal (SAR) has been the official currency of Saudi Arabia since the country was first established. The Saudi riyal is currently pegged to the US dollar at the rate of 1 US dollar = 3.75 SR.

name: Solomon Islands Dollar
bio: The Solomon Islands dollar (SBD) is the official currency of the Solomon Islands. It is subdivided into 100 cents. The symbol of the Solomon Islands dollar is $ or SI$.

name: Seychelles Rupee
bio: The Seychelles rupee (SCR) is the official currency of Seychelles. It is subdivided into 100 cents. The symbol of the Seychelles rupee is Rs. Taking into account the country’s population, Seychelles is the smallest country globally with an independent monetary policy.

name: Sudanese Pound
bio: The Sudanese pound (SDG) is the currency of the Republic of Sudan and is issued by the Central Bank of Sudan. It is subdivided into 100 piastres. The symbol of the Sudanese pound is £SD.

name: Swedish Krona
bio: The Swedish krona (SEK) has been the currency of Sweden since 1873. It is issued by the Swedish central bank, Sveriges Riksbank. The symbol of the currency is kr. One Krona is subdivided into 100 öre. In English, the currency is sometimes referred to as the Swedish crown (‘krona’ means ‘crown’ in Swedish).

name: Singapore Dollar
bio: The Singapore dollar (SGD) is the currency of the island state of Singapore. The symbol of the currency is S$. It is divided into 100 cents. The currency is issued and monitored by the Monetary Authority of Singapore.

name: St. Helena Pound
bio: The Saint Helena pound (SHP) is the official currency of Saint Helena and Ascension, two islands in the Atlantic Ocean that are members of the British Overseas Territory of Saint Helena, Ascension, and Tristan da Cunha. The Saint Helena pound is pegged to the British pound at par and both currencies are used on the island.

name: Slovenian Tolar
bio: The Slovenian tolar (SIT) was the currency of Slovenia. It was subdivided into 100 stotinov. The currency was replaced by the euro on 1st January 2007.

name: Slovak Koruna
bio: The Slovak koruna (SKK) was the currency of Slovakia. It was subdivided into 100 haliers. Its symbol was Sk. The currency’s name ‘koruna’ means ‘crown’. The Slovak koruna was replaced by the euro in January 2009.

name: Sierra Leone Leone
bio: The Sierra Leonean leone (SLL) is the official currency of Sierra Leone. The leone is subdivided into 100 cents. The currency’s symbol is Le. The Sierra Leonean leone is one of the weakest currencies globally.

name: Somali Shilling
bio: The Somalia shilling (SOS) is the official currency of Somalia. It is subdivided into 100 senti. The symbol of the Somalia shilling is Sh.So.

name: Suriname Dollar
bio: The Surinamese dollar is the currency of Suriname. It is subdivided into 100 cents. The symbol of the Surinamese dollar (SRD) is $ or Sr$.

name: Sao Tome/Principe Dobra
bio: The Sao Tome and Principe dobra (STN) is the official currency of São Tomé and Príncipe. It is represented by the symbol Db. The Sao Tome and Principe dobra is pegged to the euro at the rate of 1 EUR = 24.5 STN.

name: El Salvador Colon
bio: The Salvadoran colon (SVC) was the official currency of El Salvador until 2001. It was replaced by the US dollar with a fixed exchange rate of 1 USD = 8.75 SVC. Although the Salvadoran colon remains a legal tender, it no longer circulates and is rarely used. On 7 Sept 2021, Bitcoin became legal tender in the country, along with the US dollar. El Salvador is the first country that has adopted Bitcoin globally.

name: Syrian Pound
bio: The Syrian pound (SYP) is the official currency of Syria. It is subdivided into 100 piastres, although these coins are no longer issued. The symbol of the Syrian pound is £S or LS.

name: Swaziland Lilangeni
bio: The Swazi lilangeni (SZL) is the official currency of Eswatini. It is subdivided into 100 cents. The Swazi lilangeni is pegged to the South African rand.

name: Thai Baht
bio: The Thai baht (THB) is the official currency of the Kingdom of Thailand. The symbol of the currency is ฿. It is divided into 100 satang. The Bank of Thailand issues the currency.

name: Tajikistan Somoni
bio: The Tajikistani somoni (TJS) is the currency of Tajikistan. It is subdivided into 100 dirams. The symbol of the Tajikistani somoni is SM.

name: Turkmenistan New Manat
bio: The Turkmenistani manat (TMT) is the currency of Turkmenistan. It is subdivided into 100 tenges. The Turkmenistani manat is pegged to the US dollar at the rate of 1 USD = 3.50 TMT.

name: Tunisian Dinar
bio: The Tunisian dinar (TND) is the official currency of Tunisia. It is subdivided into 1,000 millimes. The symbol of the Tunisian dinar is DT.

name: Tongan Pa'anga
bio: The Tongan pa'anga (TOP) is the currency of Tonga and is governed by the National Reserve Bank of Tonga. The currency is not convertible and is pegged to the basket of currencies including the Australian dollar, New Zealand dollar, US dollar, and Japanese yen. The Tongan pa'anga is subdivided into 100 senitis. The symbol of the pa'anga is T$.

name: Turkish Lira
bio: The Turkish lira (TRY) is the official currency of Turkey and Northern Cyprus. The Turkish lira was introduced in 1923. The symbol of TRY is ₺.

name: Trinidad/Tobago Dollar
bio: The Trinidad and Tobago dollar (TTD) is the official currency of Trinidad and Tobago. It is subdivided into 100 cents. The symbol of the Trinidad and Tobago dollar is $ or TT$.

name: Taiwan Dollar
bio: The New Taiwan dollar (TWD) is the official currency of Taiwan. It is subdivided into 10 jiao and 100 fen. The symbol of the New Taiwan dollar is NT$.

name: Tanzanian Shilling
bio: The Tanzanian shilling (TZS) is the official currency of Tanzania. It is subdivided into 100 senti. The symbol of the Tanzanian shilling is TSh.

name: Ukraine Hryvnia
bio: The Ukrainian hryvnia (UAH) is the currency of Ukraine. Its subunit is kopiyka, one-hundredth of the hryvnia. The symbol of the Ukrainian hryvnia is ₴.

name: US Dollar
bio: The US dollar (USD) is the official currency of the United States of America. It is the world’s most widely traded currency.

name: Uruguayan Peso
bio: The Uruguayan peso (UYU) is the official currency of Uruguay. It is subdivided into 100 centésimos. The symbol of the Uruguayan peso is $ or $U.

name: Uzbekistan Som
bio: The Uzbekistani som (UZS) is the currency of Uzbekistan. It is subdivided into 100 tiyin.

name: Venezuelan Bolivar Soberano
bio: The Venezuelan bolivar soberano (VES) has been the official currency of Venezuela since 2018, replacing the bolivar fuerte (VEF). The bolivar digital (VED) was introduced on 1 Oct 2021 and is legal tender, along with the bolivar soberano. Both the US dollar and Colombian peso are used for the majority of transactions. As of 2021, VES is world's weakest currency.

name: Vietnamese Dong
bio: The Vietnamese dong (VND) is the currency of Vietnam. It was subdivided into 10 hao and 100 xu, with these coins being no longer in use due to high inflation. The currency’s symbol is ₫. As of 2021, the Vietnamese dong is the world’s third weakest currency.

name: Vanuatu Vatu
bio: The Vanuatu vatu (VUV) is the official currency of Vanuatu. The currency has no subunit. Its symbol is VT.

name: Samoan Tala
bio: The Samoan tala (WST) is the currency of Samoa. It is subdivided into 100 sene. The symbol of the Samoan tala $ or WS$.

name: CFA Franc BEAC
hypernym: central african republic, cameroon, chad, congo, equatorial guinea, gabon
bio: Central African CFA franc BEAC (XAF) is the currency of 6 countries in central Africa: Cameroon, Central African Republic, Chad, Republic of the Congo, Equatorial Guinea and Gabon. It is pegged to the euro at the rate of 1 euro = 655.957 XAF.

name: East Caribbean Dollar
hypernym: antigua barbuda anguilla dominica grenada montserrat saint kitts nevis lucia vincent
bio: The Eastern Caribbean dollar (XCD) is the currency used by 8 members of the Organisation of Eastern Caribbean States: Antigua and Barbuda, Dominica, Grenada, Saint Kitts and Nevis, Saint Lucia, Saint Vincent and the Grenadines, Anguilla, and Montserrat. The currency is subdivided into 100 cents. Its symbol is $ or EC$. The Eastern Caribbean dollar is pegged to the US dollar at the rate of 1 USD = 2.70 XCD.

name: West African CFA Franc
hypernym: benin burkina faso ivory coast mali niger senegal togo
bio: The West African CFA franc BCEAO (XOF) is the currency used by 8 independent states in West Africa: Benin, Burkina Faso, Guinea-Bissau, Ivory Coast, Mali, Niger, Senegal and Togo. It is pegged to the euro at the rate of 1 EUR = 655.957 XOF.

name: Pacific Franc Exchange
hypernym: french polynesia, new caledonia, wallis and futuna
bio: The CFP franc (XPF) is the currency of the French overseas collectives: French Polynesia, Wallis and Futuna, and New Caledonia. It is subdivided into 100 centimes. The currency symbol is ₣ or F. The CFP franc is pegged to the euro at the rate of 1 EUR = 119.3317 XPF.

name: Yemen Rial
bio: The Yemeni rial (YER) is the currency of Yemen. It is subdivided into 100 fils, although these coins are no longer in use.

name: South African Rand
bio: The South African rand (ZAR) is the currency of South Africa and is issued by the South African Reserve Bank. The South African rand has the symbol R. It is subdivided into 100 cents. The currency’s name is derived from the word ‘Witwatersrand’, which means ‘white waters’ ridge’. The ridge is where most of South Africa's gold deposits were found and where Johannesburg was built.

name: Zambian Kwacha
bio: The Zambian kwacha (ZMW) is the currency of Zambia, issued by the Bank of Zambia. The kwacha is subdivided into 100 ngwees. The symbol of the Zambian kwacha is ZK.

name: Zimbabwe Old Dollar
bio: The Zimbabwean dollar (ZWD) was the official currency of Zimbabwe from 1980 to 2009. During that time, the currency suffered three redenominations to fight high face value paper denominations caused by hyperinflation. Currencies such as the South African rand, Botswana pula, British pound, euro, US dollar, Australian dollar, Chinese yuan, Indian rupee and Japanese yen are now used as legal tender in the country.
